Category And Sub-Category Wise Analysis
Sales, Profit, and Avg Discount by Category
In [16]:
# Group by Category and calculate Sales, Profit, and Avg Discount
category_data = df.groupby('Category')[['Sales', 'Profit', 'Discount']].agg({
    'Sales': 'sum',
    'Profit': 'sum',
    'Discount': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

# Bar settings
bar_width = 0.25
x = np.arange(len(category_data['Category']))

# Plotting
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

# Sales and Profit Bars
ax1.bar(x, category_data['Sales'], width=bar_width, label='Sales', color='#87CEFA')
ax1.bar(x + bar_width, category_data['Profit'], width=bar_width, label='Profit', color='#1E90FF')
ax1.set_xlabel('Category')
ax1.set_ylabel('Sales / Profit Amount')
ax1.set_xticks(x + bar_width / 2)
ax1.set_xticklabels(category_data['Category'])
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')
ax1.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.4)

# Discount Line on Secondary Y-axis
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(x + bar_width / 2, category_data['Discount'], color='orange', marker='o', linewidth=2, label='Avg Discount')
ax2.set_ylabel('Average Discount')
ax2.legend(loc='upper right')

plt.title('Category-wise Sales, Profit & Avg Discount')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Insight: Technology leads in both sales and profit, indicating a strong market presence and margin even though with least discount. While Furniture has High Sales Still it lags in profit due to high discounts and operational costs.

# Group by Sub-Category and calculate Sales, Profit, and Avg Discount
category_data = df.groupby('Sub-Category')[['Sales', 'Profit', 'Discount']].agg({
    'Sales': 'sum',
    'Profit': 'sum',
    'Discount': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

bar_width = 0.25
x = np.arange(len(category_data['Sub-Category']))

# Plotting
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

# Sales and Profit Bar
ax1.bar(x, category_data['Sales'], width=bar_width, label='Sales', color='#87CEFA')
ax1.bar(x + bar_width, category_data['Profit'], width=bar_width, label='Profit', color='#1E90FF')
ax1.set_xlabel('Sub-Category')
ax1.set_ylabel('Sales / Profit')
ax1.set_xticks(x + bar_width / 2)
ax1.set_xticklabels(category_data['Sub-Category'], rotation=45)
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')
ax1.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.4)

# Discount Line on Secondary Y-axis
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(x + bar_width / 2, category_data['Discount'], color='orange', marker='o', label='Avg Discount')
ax2.set_ylabel('Average Discount')
ax2.legend(loc='upper right')

plt.title('Sub-Category-wise Sales, Profit, and Avg Discount')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Insight: Chairs and Phones dominate sub-category sales, while Copiers have the highest profit. Some items like Tables and Bookcases have descent sales but suffer in profit, Decrease in binders and machines's Discount can increase their profit

from IPython.display import display, HTML

# Top 5 Products by Sales
top_sales_table = (
    df.groupby("Product Name")["Sales"]
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(5)
    .reset_index()
)
top_sales_table.columns = ["Product Name", "Total Sales"]
top_sales_table["Sales Rank"] = range(1, 6)

# Top 5 Products by Profit
top_profit_table = (
    df.groupby("Product Name")["Profit"]
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(5)
    .reset_index()
)
top_profit_table.columns = ["Product Name", "Total Profit"]
top_profit_table["Profit Rank"] = range(1, 6)

# Convert tables to HTML and display side by side
sales_html = top_sales_table.to_html(index=False)
profit_html = top_profit_table.to_html(index=False)

display(HTML(f"""
<style>
    th {{
        text-align: center !important;
    }}
    td {{
        text-align: center;
    }}
</style>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between;">
    <div style="margin-right: 20px;">{sales_html}</div>
    <div>{profit_html}</div>
</div>
"""))

Order Quantity Distribution By Category and Sub-Category
In [24]:
# Group by Category and calculate the sum of Quantity
category_quantity = df.groupby('Category')['Quantity'].sum()

# Group by Sub-Category and calculate the sum of Quantity
sub_category_quantity = df.groupby('Sub-Category')['Quantity'].sum()

# Define the custom colors
category_colors = ['#51dfff', '#00aaff', '#4983ff', '#0046ff'] * (len(category_quantity) // 4 + 1)  # Repeat to match number of categories
sub_category_colors = ['#51dfff', '#00aaff', '#4983ff', '#0046ff'] * (len(sub_category_quantity) // 4 + 1)  # Repeat to match number of sub-categories

# Plotting both pie charts side by side
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 7))

# Category-wise pie chart
axes[0].pie(category_quantity, labels=category_quantity.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=category_colors[:len(category_quantity)])
axes[0].set_title('Category-wise Quantity Distribution')

# Sub-Category-wise pie chart
axes[1].pie(sub_category_quantity, labels=sub_category_quantity.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=sub_category_colors[:len(sub_category_quantity)])
axes[1].set_title('Sub-Category-wise Quantity Distribution')

# Show the pie charts
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Insight: The pie charts reveal that the Office Supplies category dominates total order quantity, especially driven by sub-categories like Binders and Paper. Meanwhile, categories like Technology and Furniture have relatively lower shares, suggesting their higher-value but lower-volume nature. Sub-categories such as Tables and Chairs contribute modestly, aligning with their bulky and less frequently ordered profile.

Profit And Sales Monthly and Yearly Trend
In [26]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Ensure dates are parsed correctly
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], errors='coerce')

# Create new columns
df['Year-Month'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M').astype(str)
df['Year'] = df['Order Date'].dt.year

# Group data
monthly = df.groupby('Year-Month')[['Sales', 'Profit']].sum().reset_index()
yearly = df.groupby('Year')[['Sales', 'Profit']].sum().reset_index()

# X positions for yearly bars
x = np.arange(len(yearly['Year']))
bar_width = 0.4

# Plotting
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(14, 10))

# --- Monthly Line Chart ---
axs[0].plot(monthly['Year-Month'], monthly['Sales'], label='Sales', color='dodgerblue', marker='o')
axs[0].plot(monthly['Year-Month'], monthly['Profit'], label='Profit', color='darkorange', marker='o')
axs[0].set_title('Monthly Sales & Profit Trend')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Amount')
axs[0].legend()
axs[0].grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
axs[0].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# --- Yearly Bar Chart ---
axs[1].bar(x - bar_width/2, yearly['Sales'], width=bar_width, label='Sales', color='dodgerblue')
axs[1].bar(x + bar_width/2, yearly['Profit'], width=bar_width, label='Profit', color='darkorange')
axs[1].set_title('Yearly Sales & Profit Comparison')
axs[1].set_xlabel('Year')
axs[1].set_ylabel('Amount')
axs[1].set_xticks(x)
axs[1].set_xticklabels(yearly['Year'])
axs[1].legend()
axs[1].grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Insight: Sales have steadily increased from 2014 to 2017, but profit hasn't followed a consistent upward trend, showing volatility. This indicates growth in volume without guaranteed improvement in profitability. November clearly dominates both sales and profit, followed by strong performance in October and December. July and February emerge as low-profit months.
Category Wise Monthly Trend Of Profit And Sales
In [27]:
# Create Year-Month column
df['Year-Month'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M').astype(str)

# Group by Year-Month and Category
cat_monthly = df.groupby(['Year-Month', 'Category'])[['Sales', 'Profit']].sum().reset_index()

# Pivot data
sales_pivot = cat_monthly.pivot(index='Year-Month', columns='Category', values='Sales')
profit_pivot = cat_monthly.pivot(index='Year-Month', columns='Category', values='Profit')

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Sales Chart
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
sales_pivot.plot(ax=plt.gca(), marker='o', linewidth=2)
plt.title('Category-wise Sales Trend Over Time', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Sales')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)

# Profit Chart
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
profit_pivot.plot(ax=plt.gca(), marker='o', linewidth=2)
plt.title('Category-wise Profit Trend Over Time', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Profit')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Insight: TheTechnology category shows consistent peaks in both sales and profit across multiple months, affirming its high-margin nature. Office Supplies demonstrates volume-driven sales but comparatively modest profits, while Furniture exhibits occasional profit dips even during high sales months, signaling possible heavy-discount promotions.
Sales vs Discount Monthly Trend
In [28]:
monthly = df.groupby('Year-Month')[['Sales', 'Discount']].mean().reset_index()

fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

# Sales line
ax1.plot(monthly['Year-Month'], monthly['Sales'], color='dodgerblue', label='Average Sales')
ax1.set_xlabel('Month')
ax1.set_ylabel('Avg Sales', color='dodgerblue')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='dodgerblue')
ax1.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# Twin axis for Discount
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(monthly['Year-Month'], monthly['Discount'], color='crimson', label='Average Discount')
ax2.set_ylabel('Avg Discount', color='crimson')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='crimson')

# Title and layout
plt.title('Monthly Average Sales vs Discount')
fig.tight_layout()
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.show()
Insight: The monthly trend line clearly reveals that higher average discounts often coincide with dips in average sales, indicating that excessive discounting may not always lead to increased revenue. For example, during certain months, a spike in discounting resulted in a decline in average sales, suggesting the importance of a balanced pricing strategy.

State Wise Sales & Profit Trends

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Assuming you have df with 'State', 'City', 'Sales', 'Profit' columns

# Group by state and calculate sum of sales and profit
state_sales_profit = df.groupby('State')[['Sales', 'Profit']].agg('sum').reset_index()

# Plot State-wise Sales
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='State', y='Sales', data=state_sales_profit, palette='Blues_d')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('State-wise Total Sales')
plt.xlabel('State')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.show()

# Plot State-wise Profit
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='State', y='Profit', data=state_sales_profit, palette='Greens_d')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('State-wise Total Profit')
plt.xlabel('State')
plt.ylabel('Total Profit')
plt.show()
Insight: Sales are highest in states like California and New York, confirming their economic weight. These should remain primary focus areas, but lower-performing states also show potential for growth. Not all high-sales states yield high profits. Some states with lower sales outperform others in terms of profitability, emphasizing the need for cost control and strategic pricing.

Final Takeaways & Strategic Suggestions

  • Technology leads in both sales and profit, making it the most valuable product category.
  • Sub-categories like Copiers and Phones show high profitability, while Tables and Bookcases incur losses even with decent sales.
  • California, New York, and Washington are top-performing states in both sales and profit. However, states like Texas and Illinois show high sales but comparatively poor profitability.
  • Significant outliers and variability exist in state-wise profit, calling for region-specific strategies rather than blanket decisions.
  • Excessive discounts in some sub-categories are not directly boosting sales showing a need to refine pricing strategies.
  • Consumer segment dominates across categories, but theres noticeable potential in Corporate and Home Office segments, especially in Technology.
  • Shipping delays spike in festive months, indicating a need for proactive supply chain management during high-demand periods.
  • November emerges as the strongest month across KPIs ideal for campaign targeting.

Suggestion: Focus on high-performing product lines with balanced discounting. Minimize loss-making sub-categories or improve cost efficiency in their delivery. Prioritize targeted strategies based on state-wise and segment-level performance.
